description: With battery inserted and all switches ON, use a multimeter to measure the voltage between the 12V and 0V lines at the load module, both ahead of and after the series diode feeding the lamp and its indicator, to verify whether correct polarity and supply voltage are actually present at the load and whether the diode is conducting., outcome='At the load module, both the Load Input Cable (+) and Load Input Cable (−) measure 0.0 V, indicating no supply voltage present at the load. The Load Protection Diode anode and cathode also both measure 0.0 V, indicating no voltage across the diode and no conduction.\nCurrent persistent circuit state [differences with the starting state]:\nNo circuit-level changes introduced by diagnostics.', precise_action_cost=70.0, cost_breakdown=[('measure_voltage', 20.0), ('measure_voltage', 20.0), ('invert_enclosure', 10.0), ('measure_voltage', 20.0)], simplified_outcome=None), DiagnosticActionResult(action=
name: Test -> Power supply output cables and first control module input cables,
description: With battery inserted, use a multimeter referenced to the power-supply negative terminal to identify which of the two power-supply output cables is actually at +12 V, then continuity‑test that cable through each inter‑module connection up to Control Module 1 input, verifying that the same physical conductor reaches the corresponding input terminal. Repeat for the 0 V return line. This checks for any mis‑connection or open between the power supply and Control Module 1., outcome='PSU Output Cable (+) is at +11.99 V relative to the PSU negative terminal, while PSU Output Cable (−) is at 0 V. Continuity tests show a short, low‑resistance path from PSU Output Cable (+) to Control Input Cable (+) 1, and from PSU Output Cable (−) to Control Input Cable (−) 1. No POLARITY INVERSION DETECTED between the PSU output cables and Control Input Cables for Module 1.\nCurrent persistent circuit state [differences with the starting state]:\nNo circuit-level changes introduced by diagnostics.', precise_action_cost=100.0, cost_breakdown=[('measure_voltage', 20.0), ('measure_voltage', 20.0), ('test_path_continuity', 30.0), ('test_path_continuity', 30.0)], simplified_outcome=None), DiagnosticActionResult(action=
name: Test -> Control modules 1–8 through-chain (12 V and 0 V lines),
description: With the battery inserted and all switches ON, use a multimeter referenced to PSU negative to measure the voltage on the presumed +12 V conductor at the input and output of each control module in sequence (CM1 in+, CM1 out+, CM2 in+, CM2 out+, … CM8 out+). In each case also confirm the corresponding 0 V line continuity. This will locate where along the series chain the +12 V (and/or 0 V) line is lost or miswired between CM1 and the load module., outcome='+12 V is present at CM1 in+, CM1 out+, CM2 in+, CM2 out+, and CM3 in+, but is lost at CM3 out+ and remains at 0 V from CM3 out+ onward through CM8 out+. The 0 V / negative line shows continuity from each control module’s in− and out− back to the PSU Output Cable (−), with increasing measured resistance along the chain.\nCurrent persistent circuit state [differences with the starting state]:\nNo circuit-level changes introduced by diagnostics.', precise_action_cost=800.0, cost_breakdown=[('measure_voltage', 20.0), ('test_path_continuity', 30.0), ('measure_voltage', 20.0), ('test_path_continuity', 30.0), ('measure_voltage', 20.0), ('test_path_continuity', 30.0), ('measure_voltage', 20.0), ('test_path_continuity', 30.0), ('measure_voltage', 20.0), ('test_path_continuity', 30.0), ('measure_voltage', 20.0), ('test_path_continuity', 30.0), ('measure_voltage', 20.0), ('test_path_continuity', 30.0), ('measure_voltage', 20.0), ('test_path_continuity', 30.0), ('measure_voltage', 20.0), ('test_path_continuity', 30.0), ('measure_voltage', 20.0), ('test_path_continuity', 30.0), ('measure_voltage', 20.0), ('test_path_continuity', 30.0), ('measure_voltage', 20.0), ('test_path_continuity', 30.0), ('measure_voltage', 20.0), ('test_path_continuity', 30.0), ('measure_voltage', 20.0), ('test_path_continuity', 30.0), ('measure_voltage', 20.0), ('test_path_continuity', 30.0), ('measure_voltage', 20.0), ('test_path_continuity', 30.0)], simplified_outcome=None), DiagnosticActionResult(action=
name: Test -> Control Module 3 internal switch path,
description: Open the inspection panel of Control Module 3. With battery inserted and all switches mechanically in the ON position, use a multimeter to measure voltage (referenced to the local 0 V line) at: (1) CM3 input + terminal, (2) the pad/terminal on the switch that connects to the input +, (3) the pad/terminal on the switch that should connect to the output + when ON, and (4) CM3 output + terminal. Also perform a continuity test across the switch contacts between input side and output side with the module removed and switch toggled ON/OFF. This will determine whether the CM3 switch or its internal wiring/open trace is interrupting the +12 V path., outcome="Voltage at Control Input Cable (+) 3 is about +11.99 V, while both the Control Switch 3 terminals and Control Output Cable (+) 3 measure 0 V. Continuity across Control Switch 3 is nominal (≈0.01 Ω), but an anomaly is reported: cable 'Control Input Cable (+) 3' has a disconnected end (port 'n' is floating; originally electrically connected to 'Control Switch 3').\nCurrent persistent circuit state [differences with the starting state]:\nNo circuit-level changes introduced by diagnostics.", precise_action_cost=115.0, cost_breakdown=[('open_inspection_panel', 5.0), ('measure_voltage', 20.0), ('invert_enclosure', 10.0), ('measure_voltage', 20.0), ('measure_voltage', 20.0), ('measure_voltage', 20.0), ('test_continuity', 20.0)], simplified_outcome=None)] 
